li.p:
This time we are looking for angles such that

                \tan(\theta)=\frac{\sin(\theta)}{\cos(\theta)}=\sqrt{3} 
            
            Since
                \sqrt{3}=\frac{\sqrt{3}/2}{1/2}=\frac{-\sqrt{3}/2}{-1/2}

            the two such angles are \frac{\pi}{3} (which corresponds to \sin(\theta)=\sqrt{3}/2 and \cos(\theta)=1/2) and \frac{4\pi}{3} (which corresponds to \sin(\theta)=-\sqrt{3}/2 and \cos(\theta)=-1/2).

solution.p:
Here, we need to decide whether to provide our answer in degrees or radians. Since we are given the interval [0,2\pi], which is radians, we will provide our answers in radians. Using our calculator in radian mode we get that 
\theta \approx 1.982 \text{ radians}
We have now found one angle in the interval [0,2\pi] such that \cos(\theta) = -0.4. However, as shown above, \theta could lie in either Quadrant II or Quadrant III. Since 1.982 is bigger than \pi/2 \approx 1.571 and smaller than \pi \approx 3.142, we know that \theta=1.982 lies in Quadrant II. Therefore, we have found the angle shown below.

Since we know the hypotenuse and the side adjacent to the angle, it makes sense for us to use the cosine function.

 \cos(\theta) \amp = \frac{9}{12} \amp\amp\text{Using the definition of the inverse} 

 \theta \amp = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{9}{12}\right) \amp\amp\text{Evaluating on our calculator} 

 \theta \amp \approx 0.723 \text{ radians} \amp\amp\text{or about } \ 41.410^\circ
